\f0\fs52 \cf0 Live Basil Gimlet\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl380\ql\qnatural

\fs44 \cf0 At Spoonbar, Scott Beattie uses herbs from a farm a half-mile down the road and keeps them alive until the moment they hit the cocktail shaker. To replicate this freshness at home, snip leaves from your garden just before mixing or buy hyrdroponic basil at the supermarket and store in a glass of water.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\ql\qnatural

\f1\b \cf0 Ingredients\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs40 \cf0 5 large basil leaves\
1 1/2 ounces gin\
3/4 ounce fresh lime juice\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\ql\qnatural
\cf0 1/2 ounce {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/22/dining/simple-syrup-recipe.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 simple syrup}}.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\ql\qnatural

\b\fs44 \cf0 Preparation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs40 \cf0 Put 4 basil leaves in a cocktail shaker and press them gently with a muddler or a wooden spoon. Add the gin, lime juice and simple syrup. Fill with ice, shake vigorously and strain into a chilled coupe or other small glass. Garnish with the remaining basil leaf.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\ql\qnatural

\fs38 \cf0 Yield: 1 drink.\
